Dear Parents and Greater Ketchikan Community,

A group of district administrators and community stakeholders met multiple days this week to update and modify the KGBSD Smart Start plan. The following is what emerged from this week’s collaborative work. As of this morning the Department of Education and Early Development notified us that they will be updating their Alaska Smart Start 2020 guidance with the new CDC recommendations. As a result, we are revising our mitigation plan and will send out updates throughout the weekend.

To read the full message:

City of Ketchikan
July 20 at 9:02 AM ·

Besides practicing basic preventive measures like handwashing, wearing a face covering, and social distancing, you can minimize your risk for getting COVID-19 by AVOIDING:
• Being in an enclosed space
• Being in a crowd or being unable to physically distance yourself from others
• Having longer interactions with people outside your household
• Being around forceful exhalations, like coughing, yelling, or singing
“When you’re thinking about places to go, things you’re doing, think about those four criteria and how you can minimize those four to minimize your risk of COVID,” says Alaska Chief Medical Officer Dr. Anne Zink.

#KGBSDTogether

Message From the Superintendent:
LETTER TO PARENTS & THE KETCHIKAN COMMUNITY

I know that there is a lot of concern about how we move into school in the fall, and I have been receiving many calls, emails, texts, and other inquiries regarding the District’s Smart Start plan. I also know that some misinformation is circulating that has caused some concern. As a result, I am providing additional information to you and the community about our current status, and some of the plans we currently have in place. This is a communication that is going out a little earlier than planned, but, with consideration for the understandable angst the unknown creates for many of our families, I hope that it will help you understand the process the district is going through to determine how to operate in the fall.

To read more: https://www.kgbsd.org/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=1206&ModuleInstanceID=9739&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=14611&PageID=5861

Phase III begins at 8:00 a.m. on Friday, May 22, 2020. We all must remember that the pandemic is not overdue to the announcement. Please remember it is because of the work we have all completed together that we are able to move into Phase Three. However, if all people are not careful and following health and safety precautions we could see a rise in COVID 19 cases.

post_text:
Dear Parent/Guardian,
We continue to be dedicated to your child’s academic and social-emotional education. Your child is invited to attend summer school June 15th through July 23rd. With social distancing mandates still in place, we will be offering summer school instruction remotely through ZOOM sessions with a daily schedule of activities. This year’s summer school will be open to ALL students enrolled in KGBSD grades K-12 and can be registered by a parent/guardian.

What would a schedule look like?
This year’s summer school will run Monday-Thursday from 9:00-12:00pm with a 45 min break for lunch from 12:00-12:45pm. After lunch, we will offer enrichment opportunities till 1:45pm. The focus of summer school will be math and literacy tasks daily with weekly science and art options. More details will follow.

To learn more and register visit: www.kgbsd.org

Dear KGBSD Parents/Guardians, Students and Staff,

As we enter into the second phase of educating students during the COVID-19 closures, the district would like to thank parents, guardians, family members, students, community and staff for coming together over the past five weeks. We have spoken with so many of you, and have taken to heart all of your input, communication, concerns, and appreciation. A lot of change has occurred in a very short time! We know this has been a stressful time for everyone involved and we continue to learn as we go. You have all responded with patience and understanding, and I cannot tell you how much it is appreciated.

>>> Click to read more.

We know this has been a stressful time for everyone involved and we continue to learn as we go. You have all responded with patience and understanding, and I cannot tell you how much it is appreciated.

>>> Click to read more.

post_text:
Greetings, Ketchikan Gateway Borough School District (KGBSD) Families!

We hope this past week of connecting with each other has been as helpful and heartwarming as it has been for us. We miss you all so much and hope you’re doing very well! After carefully considering information from our students, families, KGBSD staff, federal, state and local authorities, we are pleased to share our district plan for this coming week of April 6th - 10th.

Being in the midst of this global pandemic crisis, with our situation evolving and changing on a daily basis, our primary goals moving forward remain:
+Safety/health of our students, families and staff
+Staying connected
+Providing a variety of educational/non-educational
resources
+Focusing on everyone's social-emotional well being

We have not yet reached a place of district and community readiness to begin equitable “formal instruction” with all of our students. Rest assured, no student grades or credits will be negatively impacted during this unprecedented time.

Please click to view full parent letter.

As of 5PM this evening, the following Borough, City and Saxman facilities will be closed to the public until further notice:
Borough White Cliff Building
Borough Pat Wise Animal Shelter
City Hall
City of Ketchikan Ports and Harbors
All KPU Offices, including KPU Customer Service in the Plaza

Saxman City Hall and Community Center

The City and Borough administrative offices will continue to operate under normal business hours and staff will be available to assist citizens via online and telephonic services.

Hello KGBSD Families and Staff,

I want to share with you what the school district leadership team, teachers and staff have been working on daily to respond, prevent and prepare for during this rapidly evolving COVID-19 pandemic. We are working closely and taking direction about the COVID-19 from the State Department of Health and Social Services, the Department of Education and Early Development, Office of the Governor, CDC and Ketchikan EOC Manager and team that includes the Borough, City, Public Health and Peace Health.

Visit www.kgbsd.org for further information and regular updates.

Ketchikan Gateway Borough
March 12 at 4:56 PM ·

In response to the COVID-19 virus the Ketchikan Gateway Borough, Ketchikan Gateway Borough School District & City of Ketchikan are currently taking universal precautions as prescribed by the Centers for Disease Control (https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html). These steps include additional environmental cleanings of public facilities to include: the White Cliff Building, City Hall, Public Library, Museum, Gateway Recreation Center, Ketchikan International Airport, the Borough’s Transit Buses and Public Schools to minimize the spread of germs to our employees, residents and visitors.

Hi All,
On Friday March 6th, the school is having a Stop-Drop-And Read event at 10:45 in honor of Dr. Suess' birthday. Ms. Powers (the librarian) would love it if parents would come in and read to a class. If you would like to do so, please let us (or Ms. Powers) know! She will have a hat and book ready for you, or you can bring your own.

She would also like to let you know that she will still be having a Read Across America week, but has pushed it back to the end of March to accommodate teachers.

Happy Reading!

shared_text:
Point Higgins PTO
February 26 at 1:20 PM ·

Elections are upon us, and we are realizing our usual crew has had changes to their lives where they will not be able to participate at their usual capacity. We have such fantastic parents who rise to the occasion when donations are needed....if you have some time to give to help coordinate events such as shoe drives, book fair, conferences and adoption trees, please let us know.

If you just simply can't make the times of our meetings, please know we decide the meeting time based on our Board's schedule, so that will change. We really hope to get enough participation to be able to continue.

Our next scheduled meeting is March 5th. Elections will be April 2nd. If you are interested in becoming a board member, but can't make that date, please reach out to a Board member, or send us a PM.

Thank you for all you do!
